This project concerns the interplay between quantum field theory and cosmology. A central prediction of quantum field theory is that fields at each point in space experience an irreducible amount of fluctuation, whereas modern cosmology is based on the assumption that the very early universe underwent a phase of accelerated expansion at a staggering rate known as ``primordial inflation''. The PI and his collaborators in Europe, Asia and North America studied how the expansion of the universe affected the fluctuations of quantum fields, and how these fluctuations may have changed the expansion rate, as well as the propagation of particles and force laws. The principal results were:

(1) The observation that large corrections from quantum gravity have two distinct forms; 

(2) The demonstration of how quantum corrections to late time cosmology can explain the current phase of cosmic acceleration without violating observational constraints from the solar system;
(3) An accurate template for modeling interactions between primordial perturbations in models of inflation for which the cosmic acceleration underwent large oscillations;
(4) An accurate approximation for the effect that fluctuations of ordinary matter have on the special matter that is conjectured to cause inflation;
(5) The observation that no acceptable modification to the classical laws of physics can suppress (4) but that it may be possible to arrange for cancellations between the effects of fluctuations from ordinary matter with different spins; and
(6) The demonstration that quantum gravitational corrections to a simple kind of massless, spin zero particle (massless, conformally coupled scalars) do not become large during inflation.




This project also promoted education, training and outreach. Two Ph.D students (one of them female) were graduated during the project, both of whom hold STEM positions inside the United States. The PI's collaborations in Greece and Taiwan led to research projects for undergraduates, one of whom has been admitted to do graduate work at the University of Florida. The PI also published a popular science book designed for advanced high school students, and spoke to high school students in Florida.

